<DOC><DOCNO> AP890305-0001 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-05-89 0002EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Military     03-05 0288</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Philippines-Military,0294</SECOND><HEAD>Restructuring of Army Planned In Wake Of Corruption Allegations</HEAD><DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The military chief plans a majorrestructuring of senior echelons of the army in the wake ofallegations of widespread corruption and inefficiency, newspapersreported Sunday.   Several major newspapers quoted unnamed sources as saying Chiefof Staff Gen. Renato de Villa announced the impending changes lastFriday during a closed-door session of the Senate's defensecommittee.   The Manila Bulletin, The Manila Times and the Philippine DailyInquirer, quoted de Villa as saying the shakeup would effectregional and division commanders. No date was given for the shakeup,but the papers said it was expected to be announced in a few weeks.   The Inquirer quoted the defense committee chairman, Sen. ErnestoMaceda, as telling his colleagues that if de Villa did not movesoon, he himself would open formal investigations into theallegations of corruption.   The calls for a shakeup in the senior ranks have increasedfollowing a series of embarassing incidents. They include theNovember escape of Communist rebel commander Romulo Kintanar from aManila stockade; the takeover of a military headquarters by renegadepolicemen last January and the recent arrest of several police andmilitary officers on car theft charges in Manila.   Last week, Maceda charged that unidentified generals and colonelswere receiving thousands of dollars annually from criminalsyndicates in return for shielding them from arrest.   Maceda also challenged military claims that government forceshave gained the upper hand in the 20-year war against the communistNew People's Army.   Ten senior officers, including army commander Maj. Gen. MarianoAdalem, are scheduled to retire this year. But the newspapers saidthe shakeup will affect many senior officers not scheduled forretirement.</TEXT></DOC>